In the saturation region, the transistor functions as a voltage-controlled current source, corresponding to the model in Fig. 6.29(a). Note that $I_{D}$ is influenced by $V_{D S}$, thus it is not an ideal current source. For $V_{D S}<V_{G S}-V_{T H}$, the model must represent the triode region, yet it can still include a voltage-controlled current source, as shown in Fig. 6.29(b). If $V_{D S} \ll 2\left(V_{G S}-V_{T H}\right)$, the transistor can be regarded as a voltage-controlled resistor [Fig. 6.29(c)]. In all scenarios, the gate remains an open circuit to signify the zero gate current.

